undbreaking conceptualization of literature as a system within—and in constant interaction with—other cultural and social systems. His essays on Russian literary classics, like Pushkin’s Eugene Onegin and works by Dostoevsky and Gogol, as well as on the emerging art form of filmmaking, provide insight into the ways art and literature evolve and adapt new forms of expression. Although Tynianov was first a scholar of Russian literature, his ideas transcend the boundaries of any one genre or national tradition. Permanent Evolution gathers together for the first time Tynianov’s seminal articles on literary theory and film, including several articles never before translated into English.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMotion picturesxHistory. 0aRussian literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  a18th century Russian literature.  a19th century Russian literature.  a20th century Russian literature.  a20th century film.  aDostoevsky.  aFilm theory.  aGogol.  aPushkin.  aRussian Formalism.  aRussian Literary theory.  aRussian literary history.  aRussian poetry.  aSoviet film.  aYuri Tynianov.  acinema studies.  afilm studies.  aformalism.  aformalist theory.  aintellectual history.  alinguistics.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary theory.  aliterature.  apoetry.  asemantics.1 aKhitrova, Daria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhitrova, Daria.1 aMorse, Ainsley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRedko, Philip, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311068819140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781644690635zCo-access DOI >> click